{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lagarde_ver02/data/sn92073203/00332893087/1945100401/0330.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nFats Salvage Is\nStill In Demand\nThe fat situation is still acute,\nbecause it is unlikely that any\nappreciable supply of oils will be\nreceived from the areas surren\ndered by the Japanese for some\ntime to come, says Mrs. Estelle\nT. Smith of State College, chair\nman of the N. C. Fat Salvage Com\nmittee.\nSalvaged fats, so important in\n\u2022*the war program, are today a No.\n1 item in the reconversion plan.\nMrs. Smith urges that there be no\nlet-down in the drive for maxi\nmum used-fat collections.\nShe asks that the more than\nforty thousand home demonstra\ntion club women and all of the\nboys and girls in the 4-H clubs\nthroughout the state continue\ntheir activities in saving, collect\ning and delivering used fats to\nconcentration points in local areas.\n\u201cAgricultural workers councils\nand groups of neighborhood lead\ners in rural areas, both men and\nwomen, can be of great service\nto their country and materially\nhelp in speeding the reconversion\nprogram by consistently working\nfor the collection of used fats,\u201d\nMrs. Smith declares. \u201cWhile there\nhas been an increase in the quar\nterly quota of fats and oils for\nthe production of civilian supplies\nof soap, still the situation on oils\ncontinues to remain acute and the\nheed for the salvaging of fats in\nthe home is one of the most im\nportant points in the reconversion\nplan.\u201d\nIN MEMORIAL\nIn loving memory of our dear\nhusband and uncle. James W.\nLyall, who passed away the 7th\nof August, 1945:\nGod saw the road was getting\nrough.\nThe hills were hard to climb,\nHe gently closed His loving lov\ning eyes,\nAnd whispered \u201cPeace be Thine.\u201d\nHis weary hours, his days of pain,\nHis weary nights are past,\nHis ever patient worn out frame\nHas found sweet rest at last.\nLoving and kind in all his ways,\nUpright and just to the end of\nhis days;\nSincere and true in heart and\nmind,\nBeautiful memories he left be\nhind.\n\u2022Somewhere back of the sunset,\nWhere loneliness never dies,\nHe lives in the land of glory\n\u2019Mid the blue and gold of the\nskies.\nAnd we, who have known and\nloved him,\nAnd whose passing brought sad\ntears,\nWill cherish the memory always!\nTo brighten the drifting years.\nWife, Della Lyall, and neice, J\nMrs. C. Horton.\nObituary\nESTLE McFIELD HURLEY i\nEstle McField Hurley, son of the\nlate Mr. and Mrs. W. M. Hurley,\nwas born March 17, 1886 and de\nparted this life, August 30, 1945,'\nmaking his stay on earth. 59 years, j\n5 moriths and 13 days.\nIHe was married to Betty Shu\nmake, December 28, 1910 and to!\nthis union were born the follow\ning children: Anson and Willie,\nof Street, Md.; Gilbert, of Hokes\nsen, Del.; Jess, in the army in\nGermany; Mrs. Maryetta Powers,\nof Bina; Mrs. Ophelia Day, of\nJoppa, Md.; Stella, Bobbie Lee\nand Jackie, of Crumpler. Two of\nthe children, Lina and Ruth, pre\nceded him in death in their infan-\ncy.\nBesides the living children and\nan invalid wife, he leaves 11\ngrandchildren, one sister, Mrs.\nRoxie Brown, and other relatives\nand friends to mourn his passing.\nHe was a kind and affectionate\nhusband and a good father, and\nhe worked hard to provide the\ncomforts of life for his large fami\nly-\nHe had been in declining health\nfor the past three years and had\n'been confined tb his home and\ndsed for the past eight months.\nIn his afflictions he was pa\ntsent, and expressed his willing\nness to go. He made a profession\n-di faith in Christ as his Saviour\nabout 20 years ago and was bap\ntized into the fellowship of the\n-church.\nHe told the writer of this\nsketch that he was ready to go\nand that he felt that the Lord\nwould take care of him.\nWhile it is hard for the wife\nand children to give him up, we\nAfeel that their loss is his eternal\nSo goodbye, husband and fa\nt Sher, and may each of you so live\nWt when the summons of death I\ncomes you will be ready, and that\n'\u2022you all may be reunited on that\njpeaxjeful shore.\ni Written by W. E. Denny\nTHEY\u2019RE STILL GIVING\nARE YOlJ?\nGive Gratefully and Generously Through Our\nUNITED WAR\nFUND\nFor Our Own Allies\nMember Agencies\nUSO AMERICAN RELIEF FOR FRANCE RUSSIAN WAR RELIEF\nUNITED SEAMEN\u2019S SERVICE GREEK WAR RELIEF ASSOCIATION UNITED YUGOSLAV RELIEF FUND\nPm!ffHNE N RELIEF AMERICAN RELIEF FOR HOLLAND 000\nAMERICAN RELIEF FOR ITALY AMERICAN FIELD SERVICE\nRFT CIAN WAR RFI IFF SOCIETY UNITED LITHUANIAN RELIEF FUND REFUGEE RELIEF TRUSTEES\nUNITED CHINA RELIEF FRIENDS OF LUXEMBOURGH U. S. COMMITTEE FOR THE CARE OF\nAMERICAN RELIEF FOR AMERICAN RELIEF FOR NORWAY EUROPEAN CHILDREN\nCZECHOSLOVAKIA POLISH WAR RELIEF LOCAL BOY SCOUT FUND\nAshe County Has A Quota Os\n$5,000.00\nPresident Truman says:\n\u201cThe private agencies of the National War\nFund have a special task to do that is indis\npensable and unique.\u201d\nDo Your Part!\nDrive Opens Tomorrow\nOctober 5\nF\nz\nfHE SKYLAND POST, WEST JEFFERSON, N. C\nTHURSDAY, OCT. 4, 1945","height":"27207","width":"19956"}}
